<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB35C8527DFDFF152873CA70" blockId="24.[140,1108,166,1179]" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DFDFF152A4ACF7A" bold="true" box="[185,312,237,263]" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DFDFF152A41CF7A" box="[185,307,237,263]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" reason="1">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527C7AFF162A9ECF7A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[318,492,237,263]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527C7AFF162A9ECF7A" box="[318,492,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Hypotrix lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a relatively large moth (forewing: 
<quantity id="4CFC1591BB35C8527EC7FF152F73CF75" box="[899,1025,237,264]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="16.0" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="15.0">
15 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527EE5FF0928DFCF7B" bold="true" box="[929,941,241,262]" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">–</emphasis>
17 mm
</quantity>
) that is superficially unlike any other species in North America. Th e forewing is a hoary gray with a large entirely black crescent-shaped reniform spot that is fused posteriorly with the black orbicular spot. It is most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527E44FEAF2BA2CFE9" authority="(Draudt, 1924)" baseAuthorityName="Draudt" baseAuthorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quindiensis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527E44FEAF2896CF0C" box="[768,996,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Hypotrix quindiensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF95C585BB35C8527EBCFEAF2BBACFE9" author="Draudt M" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" pagination="1919 - 1944" refId="ref13625" refString="Draudt M (1924) 7. Band: Eulenartige Nachtfalter. In: Seitz A (1919 - 1944) Die Gross- Schmetterlinge der Erde, II. Abteilung: Die Gross-Schmetterlinge der Amerikanischen Faunengebietes. Alfred Kernen, Stuttgart, 508 pp. 96 pl." type="book chapter" year="1924">Draudt, 1924</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
that was originally described as a form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527FFEFE83285ACFE9" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[698,808,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527FFEFE8329A2CFE9" box="[698,720,379,404]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527FA5FE82285ACFE9" box="[737,808,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; it occurs from 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB35C8527EA6FE822F21CFE9" box="[994,1107,378,404]" name="Colombia" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Colombia</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB35C8527DEFFE662B90CFC5" box="[171,226,414,440]" name="Peru" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Peru</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527DA9FE662AEECFCA" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[237,412,413,439]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DA9FE662AEECFCA" box="[237,412,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Hypotrix lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527F75FE6629A2CFCA" baseAuthorityName="Draudt" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[561,720,413,440]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quindiensis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F75FE662935CFCA" box="[561,583,414,439]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F13FE6529A2CFCA" box="[599,720,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">quindiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a smaller orbicular spot (the two sides of the black mark formed by the fusion of the spots are similar in size in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527DEEFE1C2A35CF80" baseAuthorityName="Draudt" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[170,327,483,510]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quindiensis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DEEFE1C2BB2CF80" box="[170,192,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527D8AFE1B2A35CF80" box="[206,327,483,509]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">quindiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the postmedial line is an even black line (an irregular series of black dashes in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527DBFFDFF2AE8CC5C" baseAuthorityName="Draudt" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[251,410,519,545]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quindiensis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DBFFDFF2A63CC5D" box="[251,273,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527C65FDFF2AE8CC5C" box="[289,410,519,545]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">quindiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ending in a black spot on the costa), the basal line is obscure (a contrasting black spot in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527C9CFDD32908CC39" baseAuthorityName="Draudt" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[472,634,554,580]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quindiensis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527C9CFDD32A9CCC39" box="[472,494,555,580]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F45FDD22908CC39" box="[513,634,554,580]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">quindiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the hindwing is fuscous, not dirty white. In the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527CF3FDB6292ACC1A" baseAuthorityName="Draudt" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[439,600,589,616]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quindiensis">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527CF3FDB62ABFCC1A" box="[439,461,590,615]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527C9BFDB5292ACC1A" box="[479,600,589,615]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">quindiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are two rather than three coils in the vesica and appendix bursae and only the posterior half of the ductus bursae is sclerotized. 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527D97FD6C2ACECCD0" authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1852" box="[211,444,660,685]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurigera">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527D97FD6C2ACECCD0" box="[211,444,660,685]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Hypotrix purpurigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 17) and several of its South American relatives also have black reniform and orbicular spots that are frequently fused posteriorly, creating a wide V-shaped mark. Within the North American fauna the 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527E72FD2228BDCC89" box="[822,975,730,756]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">male genitalia</emphasis>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527EB7FD232BA1CD6A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527EB7FD232BA1CD6A" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Hypotrix lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527F4FFD062919CD6A" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[523,619,765,792]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F4FFD062953CD6A" box="[523,545,766,791]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F6BFD052919CD6A" box="[559,619,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differ in that only the apical part of the uncus is expanded in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527C3FFCD92A94CD47" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[379,486,800,827]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527C3FFCD92AE3CD47" box="[379,401,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527CDBFCD82A94CD47" box="[415,486,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
whereas the apical 2/3 is wide in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527E1CFCD928CACD47" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[856,952,800,827]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527E1CFCD9281CCD47" box="[856,878,801,826]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527E38FCD828CACD47" box="[892,952,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the clasper is stouter and abruptly tapered apically in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527F0BFCBC29C9CD20" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[591,699,835,862]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F0BFCBC2917CD20" box="[591,613,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F30FCBB29C9CD20" box="[628,699,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the dorsal lobe on the sacculus is much larger. Th e vesica is very different from that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527FBCFC9F282BCDFC" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[760,857,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527FBCFC9F287CCDFD" box="[760,782,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527E59FC9F282BCDFC" box="[797,857,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having much more extensive basal cluster of spines and subbasal cornuti in a longitudinally ribbed basal swelling, and the vesica has three tight medial coils rather than one as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527E8DFC562F59CDBA" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Barnes" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[969,1067,941,968]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hueco">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527E8DFC5628ADCDBA" box="[969,991,942,967]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527EABFC552F59CDBA" box="[1007,1067,941,967]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">hueco</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the 
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DF3FC282A13CD97" box="[183,353,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">female genitalia</emphasis>
the appendix bursae has a corresponding three coils to those in the vesica and the ductus bursae is more heavily sclerotized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31EEBFFBB35C8527DFDFBEE2AABCAE7" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BBBB874BB35C8527DFDFBEE2AABCAE7" blockId="24.[140,1108,166,1179]" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DFDFBEE2A85CA4D" bold="true" box="[185,503,1046,1073]" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527DFDFBEE2A22CA4D" box="[185,336,1046,1072]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" reason="1">Distribution</emphasis>
and biology.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C04C3F7BB35C8527F40FBEF29CBCA4C" authorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Lafontaine &amp; Ferris &amp; Walsh" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[516,697,1047,1073]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Hypotrix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="249" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lunata">
<emphasis id="B9706466BB35C8527F40FBEF29CBCA4C" box="[516,697,1047,1073]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Hypotrix lunata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs from southeastern Arizona (Chiricahua, Huachuca and Santa Rita Mountains) southward to the State of 
<collectingRegion id="49C07696BB35C8527EAAFBC22F26CA29" box="[1006,1108,1082,1108]" country="Mexico" name="Durango" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Durango</collectingRegion>
in northern 
<collectingCountry id="F313F8E4BB35C8527C50FBA52A19CA0A" box="[276,363,1117,1143]" name="Mexico" pageId="24" pageNumber="249">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Collecting dates range from late May to mid-September, probably representing two generations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
